 So here we are.

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:14.340
 The first thing to observe is that JSON

00:00:14.340 --> 00:00:17.820
 is really just the syntax.

00:00:17.820 --> 00:00:19.580
 So let's view source here.

00:00:19.580 --> 00:00:24.780
 And then we're also gonna view the console in this one.

00:00:24.780 --> 00:00:27.820
 Let's turn the console on.

00:00:28.940 --> 00:00:33.940
 And then, let's up a bit, come on, move up a bit.

00:00:33.940 --> 00:00:37.940
 So here's the source code.

00:00:37.940 --> 00:00:39.900
 This is just JavaScript.

00:00:39.900 --> 00:00:41.900
 There's no JSON coming from the server,

00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:43.260
 it's just JavaScript.

00:00:43.260 --> 00:00:44.660
 And I'm doing an assignment statement.

00:00:44.660 --> 00:00:49.660
 This is the syntax for a JavaScript object constant,

00:00:49.660 --> 00:00:54.900
 open curly brace, and then a series of string,

00:00:54.900 --> 00:00:56.740
 key value, key value, key value,

00:00:56.740 --> 00:00:58.540
 and the values can be strings,

00:00:58.540 --> 00:01:03.400
 they can be numbers, they can be booleans,

00:01:03.400 --> 00:01:05.260
 they can be arrays, and they object,

00:01:05.260 --> 00:01:08.740
 you can even have an object within the object, right?

00:01:08.740 --> 00:01:11.700
 And so all we're doing here is creating a variable

00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:14.700
 called who in JavaScript and then console logging it.

00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:18.420
 And son of a gun, if that object,

00:01:18.420 --> 00:01:20.660
 this is a parsed object, right?

00:01:20.660 --> 00:01:21.860
 That is the JavaScript.

00:01:21.860 --> 00:01:23.780
 I could have made a syntax error in here,

00:01:23.780 --> 00:01:26.140
 and then JavaScript would say syntax error.

00:01:26.140 --> 00:01:27.660
 But if that syntax is correct,

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:32.660
 that is just the syntax for a JavaScript object constant.

00:01:32.660 --> 00:01:36.360
 And so the brilliance of JSON was,

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:41.900
 let's send that exact syntax back and forth

00:01:41.900 --> 00:01:43.860
 across the network, right?

00:01:43.860 --> 00:01:46.220
 That was the brilliance of it, okay?

00:01:46.220 --> 00:01:50.940
 So let's actually do that in the simplest possible way.

00:01:50.940 --> 00:01:55.940
 So it means that we can build views inside the browser

