 it does a time sleep, which is actually quite foolish,

00:02:25.200 --> 00:02:28.600
 but I do that so you can kind of see when things start

00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:30.940
 and then when things finish.

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:33.780
 And so we have sitting here, this is Python now.

00:02:33.780 --> 00:02:36.180
 And the ironic thing is this the syntax

00:02:36.180 --> 00:02:38.700
 for a Python dictionary is the same

00:02:38.700 --> 00:02:42.420
 as the syntax for a JavaScript object.

00:02:42.420 --> 00:02:45.980
 I'd love to know like how explicitly that was.

00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:48.700
 Both syntaxes, I mean, it's a sensible syntax.

00:02:48.700 --> 00:02:50.140
 If I was inventing a language,

00:02:50.140 --> 00:02:52.060
 I might use this exact same syntax.

00:02:52.060 --> 00:02:56.020
 And so it's beautiful that JavaScript object syntax

00:02:56.020 --> 00:03:00.420
 and Python constants for dictionaries

00:03:00.420 --> 00:03:02.260
 are pretty much the same thing.

00:03:02.260 --> 00:03:04.500
 And so we simply serialize these things,

00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:06.240
 send them out and deserialize them.

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:08.880
 So what's going on in this JSON fun

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:11.300
 is we're sending back a JSON response.

00:03:11.300 --> 00:03:15.300
 In the normal situation, in this home view,

00:03:15.300 --> 00:03:18.240
 home view of course is this view right here,

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:20.620
 we are sending back, this render request

00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:23.780
 is sending back an HTTP response.

00:03:23.780 --> 00:03:26.380
 I'm not, I import it, but I don't use it.

00:03:26.380 --> 00:03:28.860
 The return value from render,

00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:32.100
 which takes the request object fetch and optional context,

00:03:32.100 --> 00:03:35.060
 that is an HTTP response.

00:03:35.060 --> 00:03:36.660
 And so it knows that it HTML.

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:39.780
 And so if we just, if we do a view source on this one,

00:03:39.780 --> 00:03:41.780
 not view source, let's do this.

00:03:41.780 --> 00:03:44.580
 Browser tools, web developer tools,

00:03:44.580 --> 00:03:46.100
 let's go to the network tab.

00:03:46.100 --> 00:03:48.180
 Let's hit refresh on this one.

00:03:48.180 --> 00:03:51.180
 And if we take a look at the request response cycle,

00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:53.820
 response headers are like text HTML.

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:57.540
 And that's because this view,

00:03:57.540 --> 00:04:01.220
 the home view is returning an HTTP response.

00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:04.740
 And in that Django is setting all these things

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:07.300
 like content length and content type.

00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:10.700
 But now we're gonna send back a JSON response.

00:04:10.700 --> 00:04:15.180
 So we're telling, we're telling Django

00:04:15.180 --> 00:04:16.860
 that we wanna send back JSON.

00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:18.740
 And here's our dictionary in Python.

00:04:18.740 --> 00:04:23.380
 So please serialize that as JSON,

00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:26.540
 send it back and set the headers correctly.

00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:29.460
 So if we look at this one and go in the network tab,

00:04:29.460 --> 00:04:31.220
 when you hit refresh,

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:33.180
 we see that there's a get request

00:04:33.180 --> 00:04:37.420
 and the response headers now are quite different.

00:04:37.420 --> 00:04:39.780
 Application JSON, it's got a content length,

00:04:39.780 --> 00:04:41.140
 et cetera, et cetera.

00:04:41.140 --> 00:04:43.420
 And if we look at the response,

00:04:43.420 --> 00:04:46.660
 now my browser is doing like clever stuff making it pretty,

00:04:46.660 --> 00:04:48.220
 but let's just look at the raw thing.

00:04:48.220 --> 00:04:52.660
 This is the serialized key value store.

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:56.740
 This is literally the text that came back from the browser.

00:04:56.740 --> 00:04:58.260
 Our browsers are trying to help us out.

00:04:58.260 --> 00:05:01.700
 They're parsing it and turning it into a JavaScript object

00:05:01.700 --> 00:05:03.900
 and showing it to us, right?

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:06.180
 And so raw, and this in up here,

00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:07.980
 you can see it says raw as well.

00:05:07.980 --> 00:05:10.660
 You can go back and forth and see what's actually sent.

00:05:10.660 --> 00:05:15.660
 So this string is created by JSON response when passed that.

00:05:16.100 --> 00:05:19.360
 Now that's serialization, deserialization.

00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:22.060
 And I guess I call attention to it,

00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:23.300
 but you can almost ignore it

00:05:23.300 --> 00:05:28.300
 'cause it works so amazingly smoothly, okay?

00:05:28.300 --> 00:05:31.180
 And so that is sort of the basic mechanisms

00:05:31.180 --> 00:05:34.060
 of retrieving and producing.

00:05:34.060 --> 00:05:39.060
 We produce the JSON inside our Python code, inside our view,

00:05:39.060 --> 00:05:42.700
 and then we send it back to the browser.

00:05:42.700 --> 00:05:46.780
 And in this case, when we're doing just plain old JSON fun,

00:05:46.780 --> 00:05:52.580
 we're doing a GET request in the browser, okay?

00:05:52.580 --> 00:05:54.620
 But that's not typically how it's done.

00:05:54.620 --> 00:05:56.300
 We do this to debug stuff, right?

00:05:56.300 --> 00:05:59.460
 We go to these JSON URLs to see if they're blowing up.

00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:01.620
 Because if the JSON URL blows up,

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:03.060
 let me see if I can make it blow up.

00:06:03.060 --> 00:06:04.640
 Let's see if I can make it blow up.

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:05.480
 I don't know.

00:06:05.480 --> 00:06:09.420
 Let me take this comma out, right?

00:06:09.420 --> 00:06:11.020
 I'll take this comma out.

00:06:11.020 --> 00:06:13.260
 So that means I'm gonna have a syntax error.

00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:18.100
 Oh, my server was so bad.

00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:19.400
 My server won't write.

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:27.460
 Can't make a mistake if I try.

00:06:27.460 --> 00:06:28.420
 Let's see if my server starts.

00:06:28.420 --> 00:06:30.820
 Okay, at least my server restarted on that one.

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:33.760
 So now maybe I'll get a 500 error or something.

00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:34.600
 Oops.

00:06:40.180 --> 00:06:41.820
 Okay, so here's the key.

00:06:41.820 --> 00:06:43.380
 So what you're going to find

00:06:43.380 --> 00:06:47.020
 is that when this fetch happens,

00:06:47.020 --> 00:06:48.580
 you're going to get a 500 error.

00:06:48.580 --> 00:06:49.980
 And this is the output of it.

00:06:49.980 --> 00:06:51.780
 Like it goes bad.

00:06:51.780 --> 00:06:54.660
 Now the problem is, is you're going to have trouble later

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:57.280
 when we're doing JSON using fetch.

00:06:57.280 --> 00:06:59.180
 When things go wrong,

00:06:59.180 --> 00:07:01.700
 you need to be able to find this response.

00:07:01.700 --> 00:07:03.180
 It won't show up in your browser.

00:07:03.180 --> 00:07:07.180
 It shows up in your debugger, right?

00:07:07.180 --> 00:07:10.740
 And so the point is, is these are harder to debug,

00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:13.540
 but sometimes you go to the URL explicitly

00:07:13.540 --> 00:07:15.660
 and at least you see its output.

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:18.320
 And this is an output where I made a mistake.

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:21.860
 And okay, so let's just fix it all.

00:07:21.860 --> 00:07:23.180
 Make sure it's working.

00:07:23.180 --> 00:07:24.340
 So the rest of it worked.

00:07:24.340 --> 00:07:25.660
 Is it working?

00:07:25.660 --> 00:07:26.500
 Yes, it's working.

00:07:26.500 --> 00:07:29.100
 Okay, so you got that.

00:07:29.100 --> 00:07:31.140
 So there's a special kind of view

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:33.420
 and a special kind of response type,

00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:37.100
 a JSON response, and we pass it a key value store,

00:07:37.100 --> 00:07:40.100
 which in Python is a dictionary.

00:07:40.100 --> 00:07:44.260
 Okay, enough of going directly.

00:07:44.260 --> 00:07:46.220
 Now we're going to use the fetch API

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:47.460
 'cause that's really what we wanna do.

00:07:47.460 --> 00:07:49.020
 We wanna fetch this data

00:07:49.020 --> 00:07:50.540
 and then we wanna do something with it,

00:07:50.540 --> 00:07:53.720
 perhaps show it in the user interface.

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:56.900
 So I have a couple of different bits of code here.

00:07:56.900 --> 00:07:58.260
 There's two ways to do this.

00:07:58.260 --> 00:07:59.100
 If you look at fetch,

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:03.880
 there's prom syntax and there is async await.

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:07.200
 And you can have a good time

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:09.820
 if you go to your search engine and type.

00:08:09.820 --> 00:08:12.760
 Which is better, promises or async await?

00:08:12.760 --> 00:08:15.860
 And the answer is you have a lot of reading to do

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:17.140
 'cause there's a lot of opinions

00:08:17.140 --> 00:08:20.780
 as to whether promise syntax or async await.

00:08:20.780 --> 00:08:23.640
 So let's take a quick look at this code.

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:29.580
 My opinion is this is the promise syntax

00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:32.060
 where you start an asynchronous action

00:08:32.060 --> 00:08:34.380
 and it returns a promise and then you wait

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:37.940
 for when the promise resolves, you run some code.

00:08:37.940 --> 00:08:40.740
 And that code itself might return another promise

00:08:40.740 --> 00:08:43.460
 and then when that second promise resolves,

00:08:43.460 --> 00:08:45.380
 it runs some more code.

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:48.980
 And then we have like a dot catch to say

00:08:48.980 --> 00:08:52.020
 if something goes wrong in any of these three things,

00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:55.340
 the starting, the first asynchronous step,

00:08:55.340 --> 00:08:56.940
 the second asynchronous step,

00:08:56.940 --> 00:08:59.060
 catch it and then give us an error.

00:09:00.060 --> 00:09:04.460
 And so a lot of people tend to use this syntax here

00:09:04.460 --> 00:09:08.020
 because it's succinct.

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:12.540
 The async code I think is way more powerful,

00:09:12.540 --> 00:09:14.140
 feels more powerful to me

00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:19.100
 because what you do is you do the fetch

00:09:19.100 --> 00:09:21.820
 and you get back a value.

00:09:21.820 --> 00:09:23.300
 Now that doesn't mean,

00:09:23.300 --> 00:09:25.140
 that just means the fetch has started

00:09:25.140 --> 00:09:28.920
 but you can check for the error on that fetch

00:09:28.920 --> 00:09:31.660
 with a catch there and do something there

00:09:31.660 --> 00:09:34.580
 and like quit and stop and not do the rest of it.

00:09:34.580 --> 00:09:37.260
 Again, it's doing effectively a simple thing here.

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:39.100
 So you notice here I can console log it,

00:09:39.100 --> 00:09:41.180
 that doesn't mean the fetch is finished.

00:09:41.180 --> 00:09:43.220
 But now what I can do is I can use an await

00:09:43.220 --> 00:09:46.060
 to say, wait a second, finish this.

00:09:46.060 --> 00:09:47.220
 I'm gonna just wait.

00:09:47.220 --> 00:09:51.480
 Now this is making it at,

00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:53.660
 I mean, I've said before that you're

00:09:53.660 --> 00:09:54.880
 in a threaded environment,

00:09:54.880 --> 00:09:58.360
 you can't wait inside of JavaScript code.

00:09:58.360 --> 00:09:59.620
 This is not really waiting.

00:09:59.620 --> 00:10:01.940
 What this is doing, when you see the await,

00:10:01.940 --> 00:10:05.160
 it's almost like the code has been broken into two halves.

00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:08.820
 It runs this half and then when you say await,

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:11.100
 it holds on to this half, right?

00:10:11.100 --> 00:10:13.200
 Grabs the rest of the code

00:10:13.200 --> 00:10:15.860
 and makes that be an event to be run.

00:10:15.860 --> 00:10:20.380
 And so this await syntax does all that splitting of code,

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:22.100
 creating the event,

00:10:22.100 --> 00:10:25.380
 indicating that the last half of this code

00:10:25.380 --> 00:10:27.300
 is supposed to be run as a result of the event.

00:10:27.300 --> 00:10:31.380
 So it's basically a way to kinda split this code in half

00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:33.780
 and then when the event finishes,

00:10:33.780 --> 00:10:34.700
 it's gonna pick up here.

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:36.820
 But we get to pretend it's procedural.

00:10:36.820 --> 00:10:39.420
 We get to pretend we're in Python

00:10:39.420 --> 00:10:42.660
 and we get to pretend that we are doing an input

00:10:42.660 --> 00:10:44.720
 and waiting for the user to type whatever,

00:10:44.720 --> 00:10:48.820
 or a request.retriever, whatever.

00:10:48.820 --> 00:10:51.180
 And the key thing this await says,

00:10:51.180 --> 00:10:53.500
 I understand that what I'm about to do is

00:10:54.620 --> 00:10:57.740
 I've got an effective promise and it's started

00:10:57.740 --> 00:10:58.660
 but not finished,

00:10:58.660 --> 00:11:02.820
 but I want to stop my current line of execution

00:11:02.820 --> 00:11:05.420
 until it finishes, okay?

00:11:05.420 --> 00:11:06.900
 So there are two ways to do it.

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:08.420
 You can do promises.

00:11:08.420 --> 00:11:11.380
 You just look at this and you see that the await

00:11:11.380 --> 00:11:13.340
 is a much longer bit of code,

00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:17.500
 partly because I put a lot more error checking into it

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:19.620
 and I got a lot of console logs, et cetera.

00:11:19.620 --> 00:11:23.380
 And if you're doing something like react or a review

00:11:23.380 --> 00:11:26.460
 or some kind of a progressive web application,

00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:30.340
 you want the kind of control I think that await does.

00:11:30.340 --> 00:11:34.340
 But in a normal thing, it's like do this thing.

00:11:34.340 --> 00:11:37.540
 It works 99.99% of the time.

00:11:37.540 --> 00:11:38.800
 Oh yeah, and there's a message.

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:40.260
 All you're gonna do is put up an alert box.

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:44.140
 So again, you can really argue both ways,

00:11:44.140 --> 00:11:46.140
 whether the promise pattern

00:11:46.140 --> 00:11:50.260
 or the async await pattern works better.

00:11:50.260 --> 00:11:54.580
 So let's just look through this code right now.

